# Step 2: Auth System Completion

## Phase 1: Planning
- [/] Explore existing auth code (models, routers, oauth2, schemas)
- [ ] Design refresh token architecture
- [ ] Create implementation plan and get user approval

## Phase 2: Backend — Refresh Token Infrastructure
- [ ] Add refresh token model/storage (Redis or DB)
- [ ] Create `/auth/refresh` endpoint
- [ ] Implement refresh token rotation (one-time-use)
- [ ] Set HttpOnly cookie for refresh token
- [ ] Add `/auth/logout` endpoint with server-side invalidation
- [ ] Update existing login endpoints to issue refresh tokens

## Phase 3: Frontend — Auto-Refresh Flow
- [ ] Update API client to handle token refresh on 401
- [ ] Remove access token from localStorage (use memory only)
- [ ] Add silent refresh on app load
- [ ] Handle refresh failure gracefully (redirect to login)

## Phase 4: Tests
- [x] Refresh token issuance on login
- [x] Refresh rotation and ONE-TIME-USE security
- [x] Server-side logout invalidation
- [x] Logout + Reset password integration
- [x] Expired token edge cases
- [x] Google OAuth refresh token flow

## Phase 5: Verify
- [ ] All tests pass
- [ ] npm run build passes
- [ ] Manual browser testing
- [ ] Push to feature branch, CI green, merge
